[Syrus having delivered the former part qs his speech in a careless manner, now turns and addresses the servants within] It is diverting here to observe how Syrus divides his discourse between Demea and those to whom he had given the fish in charge. This was making pretty free with his master’s brother. The rogue knew that Demea was little regarded by his master’s family, and that makes him the more presuming. The poet, too, has so contrived it as to raiae Demea’s astonishment still more, and fill him with reflections of the approaching ruin that threatened his brother’s family. —- 23. Congrum.
